## Naming: ccb + BEM

- All new CSS classes MUST be prefixed with `ccb-`.
- Use BEM naming:
  - Block: `.ccb-<block>`
  - Element: `.ccb-<block>__<element>`
  - Modifier: `.ccb-<block>--<modifier>`
  - State (optional): `.is-active`, `.is-loading` (only when it matches existing patterns)

## Scope & collisions

- Always scope styles under a plugin root wrapper when possible to avoid theme conflicts.
- Do not write broad selectors (e.g., `div p a`, `input`, `.button`) unless strictly necessary and already used by the plugin.

## Specificity & structure

- Avoid deep nesting (max ~2 levels).
- Prefer class selectors over tag selectors.
- Keep modifiers separate; avoid `&--mod` chains that create high specificity.

## Theme style override pattern (required for form controls and links)

- To override theme styles reliably, do NOT use global element selectors like `input {}` or `a {}`.
- Use an explicit ccb-prefixed utility/override class and apply it directly on elements:
  - `input.ccb-<control-class>`
  - `textarea.ccb-<control-class>`
  - `select.ccb-<control-class>`
  - `button.ccb-<control-class>`
  - `a.ccb-<link-class>`
- Prefer this pattern over increasing selector specificity or using `!important`.
- Keep these override classes minimal and consistent across the UI.

## Practical constraints

- Follow existing codebase conventions if they differ in specific directories (legacy vs new stack).
- Do not rename existing classes unless explicitly requested (may be used in templates/JS).
